              "text": "Researchers are investigating the role of LPS in triggering inflammatory responses in the gut.",
              "citation": {
                "source": "幻辭AI",
                "author": "Gemini",
                "note": "gemini-2.5-flash-lite"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "Lipopolysaccharide, or LPS, is a major component of the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria.",
              "citation": {
                "source": "幻辭AI",
                "author": "Gemini",
                "note": "gemini-2.5-flash-lite"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "The immune system recognizes LPS as a foreign molecule, often leading to a strong reaction.",
              "citation": {
                "source": "幻辭AI",
                "author": "Gemini",
                "note": "gemini-2.5-flash-lite"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "Studies show that LPS can activate specific immune cells, influencing the body's defense mechanisms.",
              "citation": {
                "source": "幻辭AI",
                "author": "Gemini",
                "note": "gemini-2.5-flash-lite"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "Isolating LPS from bacterial samples is a standard procedure in many immunology labs.",
              "citation": {
                "source": "幻辭AI",
                "author": "Gemini",
                "note": "gemini-2.5-flash-lite"
              }
            }
